          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an independent consultant on Schedule C. How does qualifying work?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Independent consultant Schedule C 1099 income qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a> with 24-month averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. Independent consultant deductions for home office, professional liability insurance, business development, technology platform fees, and travel between client engagements flow through Schedule C. We document 2 complete 1040s with Schedule C plus 1099-NECs from each client engagement plus business bank statements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a fractional CFO across 3 client engagements. Does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Fractional CFO and interim executive consultant income across multi-client engagement portfolios qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> with 24-month averaging smoothing engagement-portfolio variation. Multi-client retainer arrangements (typically $30K-$80K monthly per client) plus project-based add-on work produces aggregate annual Schedule C $300K-$800K typical for established fractional executive consultants. We document each client engagement through 1099-NECs and retainer agreements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for a consultant mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on channel. MBB / Big 4 W-2 employee: two W-2s, current pay stubs, HR compensation letter documenting tier, base, signing bonus structure, performance bonus history, and continuing employment status. MBB / Big 4 partner: Form 1065 partnership returns with K-1s for 2 years, Schedule L, partnership agreement, capital account history. Accenture / publicly listed firm: W-2 + LTIP grant documentation with vesting schedule + brokerage statements showing prior RSU vest. Independent / fractional: two complete 1040s with Schedule C, 1099-NECs from each client, business bank statements, retainer agreements if fractional.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My promotion came with substantial raise. How is that treated?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">MBB and most consulting firms operate up-or-out structures with substantial promotion-tied raises at each successful advancement step (30-45% typical for Associate-to-Engagement-Manager). Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the promotion-tied raise is treated as permanent base adjustment for the new tier (not non-continuing one-time event). We document the promotion through HR letter showing the tier advancement and new base salary.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My MBB capital contribution to make partner was substantial. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">MBB capital contribution to partnership (typically $200K-$500K depending on firm and partner tier) creates capital account at the firm. Capital contribution may have been funded through firm-arranged loans or personal funds. We document the capital contribution structure and capital account status. The capital account doesn&rsquo;t directly qualify income but supports balance sheet narrative for Jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for consultants?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for consultants are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. MBB W-2 pre-partner and partner K-1 both achieve strong Conventional Conforming and Jumbo outcomes at standard pricing when proper channel-specific documentation supports the file.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does IRC Section 199A QBI affect me as a consultant?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Consulting services is explicitly listed as Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a>. Partners and independent consultants face QBI deduction phase-out at higher income (2024 thresholds: $383,900 joint, $241,950 single, fully phased out at $483,900 joint and $341,950 single). Same SSTB treatment as legal and accounting. Unfavorable QBI vs non-SSTB professions but doesn&rsquo;t affect mortgage qualifying directly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering leaving MBB to start independent consulting. How should I time my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Channel transitions from MBB W-2 or partner K-1 to independent Schedule C create new-employment / new-business underwriting where the new structure doesn&rsquo;t yet have 2 years history. Strategic options: (1) close mortgage BEFORE the transition using established MBB history; (2) wait 12-24 months post-transition to establish independent Schedule C history; (3) document early client engagements with retainer agreements showing income capacity. Consulting transitions often produce strong combined-spouse qualifying once both establish.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My signing bonus has vesting over 2 years. How is that counted?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Multi-year signing bonus vesting (commonly Year 1 + Year 2 at post-MBA MBB Associate hire, sometimes 3-year vesting at lateral senior hires) qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> as continuing variable income during the active vesting period. Documented through HR letter showing the bonus structure and vesting schedule. The vesting structure parallels wirehouse forgivable loan recruiting structure documented on our financial advisor sales sub-page.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also in consulting or finance. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-consultant households or consultant-financial-services households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full channel-appropriate analysis (B3-3.1-01 W-2, B3-3.4-02 partnership K-1, B3-3.3-02 Schedule C). Combined household income from two MBB Engagement Managers commonly $580K-$700K supports $1.4M-$1.8M qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse consultant files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Six reasons: (1) MBB signing bonus classified as "non-continuing hire bonus" without recognizing multi-year vesting structure; (2) MBB performance bonus classified as "discretionary not stable" without recognizing pattern continuity; (3) MBB partner K-1 lumpy partnership distribution undercounted without Form 1084 partnership-level addbacks; (4) Accenture RSU refused as "speculative future stock" without recognizing NYSE-listed continuing market value; (5) Bain ESOP misread or not properly classified; (6) independent / fractional Schedule C project-based variation treated as instability. The income is all there and documentable &mdash; the file needs a broker who reads consultant channel-specific structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Practice area matters at MBB. How does that affect mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Practice area affects partner comp tier but not mortgage qualifying mechanics directly. MBB partners in high-fee practice areas (private equity due diligence, M&amp;A advisory, transformation) commonly earn elevated K-1 reflecting practice profitability and client mix. The mortgage qualifying mechanic is identical (B3-3.4-02 K-1 analysis with Form 1084 partnership addbacks) &mdash; only the dollar amount differs by practice area allocation within the partnership.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m at tier 2 strategy (Booz Allen, A.T. Kearney, Roland Berger, L.E.K., Oliver Wyman). Is qualifying different?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Tier 2 strategy consulting firms structure compensation similarly to MBB with pre-partner W-2 + bonus and partner K-1 (for private firms) or W-2 + RSU (for publicly listed like Booz Allen NYSE: BAH or Oliver Wyman as Marsh McLennan NYSE: MMC subsidiary). Compensation tier is typically below MBB at equivalent career stage but follows the same qualifying mechanics under B3-3.1-01 / B3-3.4-02 / B3-3.1-09 frameworks.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m at Big 4 consulting. How does qualifying differ from MBB?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Big 4 consulting partners (Deloitte Consulting, PwC Strategy&amp; / Consulting, EY-Parthenon / EY Consulting, KPMG Advisory) receive K-1 partnership distributions under the same B3-3.4-02 framework as MBB partners. Big 4 consulting partner K-1 commonly $400K-$2M+, comparable to MBB Principal/Partner tier but below MBB Senior Partner tier. Big 4 consulting practices are integrated with broader Big 4 partnership (see our CPA / Accountant sub-page for Big 4 partnership tier details).</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My firm got acquired by PE. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">PE acquisition of mid-tier and boutique consulting firms is increasingly common, mirroring parallel PE-backed CPA firm and RIA consolidator transactions. Post-acquisition structures typically include cash + multi-year earnouts + rollover equity in the holding entity. We document the acquisition terms, ongoing W-2 or partner status, rollover equity vesting schedule, and earnout payment schedule. Multi-source documentation under B3-3.1-01 + B3-3.4-02 covers the combined picture.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM for high-deduction independent consultants. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement framework. Useful when Schedule C deductions are substantial enough that Form 1084 addbacks alone don&rsquo;t produce desired qualifying income, or when independent consultants prefer simpler documentation. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election as an independent consultant?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $250K+ annual net Schedule C income for independent consultants, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a>. S-corp involves paying W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $120K-$200K for independent consultant owner-operators) and taking remaining net as K-1 distributions. Coordinate with your CPA.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering moving from MBB Partner to industry (CEO / COO role at portfolio company). How should I time my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Channel transitions from MBB partner K-1 to industry C-suite W-2 + RSU at private equity portfolio company or public company create new-employment underwriting where the new employer doesn&rsquo;t yet have 2 years W-2. Strategic options: (1) close mortgage BEFORE the transition using established MBB partner history; (2) wait 12-24 months post-transition; (3) coordinate timing with the industry role&rsquo;s vesting and bonus structure. Industry C-suite roles at PE portfolio companies commonly include substantial equity participation covered in our Corporate Executives hub.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for consultants?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Some lenders offer "professional loan" programs that include consultants alongside doctors, attorneys, and CPAs. These programs vary in availability and pricing. What matters most is finding a broker who understands consultant channel-specific qualifying: B3-3.1-01 MBB W-2 + signing + bonus, B3-3.1-09 Accenture and tier 2 publicly listed RSU vesting, B3-3.4-02 MBB and Big 4 partner K-1, and B3-3.3-02 independent Schedule C. Conventional Conforming and Jumbo done right outperforms specialty product chasing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer. Consultant files benefit from substantial runway because of channel-specific qualifying (W-2 vs K-1 vs Schedule C), multi-year partnership K-1 documentation for partners, Form 1084 cash-flow addback analysis at the partnership level, RSU vesting analysis for Accenture and publicly listed firms, multi-client retainer documentation for fractional executives, and possible coordination with firm HR for compensation letter.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What HR or firm documentation should I request?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For MBB / Big 4 W-2 employees: HR compensation letter covering career tier (Analyst, Associate, EM, AP, Principal), base salary, signing bonus structure with vesting, performance bonus history, promotion-tied raises, and continuing employment status. For partners: partnership agreement, capital account statement, Form 1065 partnership returns with K-1s for 2 years, Schedule L for cash-flow addback analysis, partnership compensation methodology documentation. For Accenture / publicly listed: W-2 + LTIP grant documentation with vesting schedule + brokerage statements showing prior RSU vest. For independent / fractional: 1099-NECs from each client, Schedule C with all worksheets, business bank statements, retainer agreements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

